## рџ”µ Cron Jobs

| Command | What it Does | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `ls /etc/cron.d/` | List all cron job configs | `ls /etc/cron.d/` |
| `cat /etc/cron.d/*` | Read all cron job configs | `cat /etc/cron.d/*` |
| `crontab -l` | List current user's cron jobs | `crontab -l` |
| `cat /etc/crontab` | Read system wide cron config | `cat /etc/crontab` |

**Cron Schedule Quick Reference:**
| Schedule | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `* * * * *` | Every minute |
| `0 * * * *` | Every hour |
| `0 0 * * *` | Every day at midnight |
| `*/5 * * * *` | Every 5 minutes |
| `@reboot` | Once at system startup |

**Privilege Escalation via Cron вЂ” What to Look For:**
- Cron jobs running as root or privileged users
- Scripts executed by cron that are writable by you
- Cron jobs writing sensitive data to world-readable locations
- Wildcard usage in cron scripts (can be exploited)

